Here's a C++ function that takes a std::string containing Markdown text and returns a std::string containing HTML text:

```cpp
// Function name: MarkdownToHTML
std::string MarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown_text)
{
    std::string html_text;
    // Read the markdown text into a stream.
    std::ifstream markdown_stream(markdown_text);
    if (!markdown_stream.is_open()) {
        // Handle error opening the stream.
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to open markdown text file.");
    }

    // Read the entire text file into a buffer.
    std::stringstream buffer;
    buffer << markdown_stream.rdbuf();

    // Convert the buffer to HTML.
    try {
        // Get the buffer as UTF-8 encoded bytes.
        const char* utf8 = buffer.str().c_str();
        // Call the MarkdownToHTML function in the Boost library.
        const auto html_bytes = boost::markdown::to_html(utf8);

        // Convert the HTML bytes to UTF-8 encoded bytes and assign them to the output string.
        std::array<unsigned char, 4> byte_count = { 0 };
        html_bytes.copy(byte_count, byte_count + 4);
        for (int i = 0; i < byte_count[0]; i++) {
            html_text += (char)byte_count[i];
        }
    } catch (const boost::markdown::parser_error& e) {
        // Handle any parsing errors.
        throw std::runtime_error("Parsing error converting Markdown to HTML.");
    } catch (const boost::markdown::runtime_error& e) {
        // Handle any runtime errors.
        throw std::runtime_error("Runtime error converting Markdown to HTML.");
    } catch (const boost::system::system_error& e) {
        // Handle any system errors. This might be caused by an invalid UTF-8 string, so check that first. If not, check that there's enough bytes in the string for the HTML text length. Otherwise, throw an error.  Also catch other system errors here too if needed.  For example, an out of memory error while trying to parse an invalid UTF-8 string is also a system error that should be handled here too, since we can't expect memory to be available for HTML conversion after trying to parse an invalid UTF-8 string as if it was valid UTF-8 string, which would lead to out of memory errors when trying to convert invalid UTF-8 string to HTML.  If you need this for some reason, you can use boost::system/throw exceptions here too like how I did for boost::markdown/parser_error exception here above.  You would do this by wrapping the call in boost::system/throw exceptions as follows: `try { boost::system/throw exceptions call to convert UTF-8 string to HTML } catch (const boost/system/exception& e) { ... handle exception ... }`  If you need this for some reason, you can use boost/system/throw exceptions here too like how I did for boost/markdown/parser_error exception here above.`

